<doc id="1086619" wikidata="Q6154788" url="?curid=1086619" title="Riemannian submanifold">
<text>A Riemannian submanifold formula_1 of a Riemannian manifold formula_2 is a submanifold formula_1 of formula_2 equipped with the Riemannian metric inherited from formula_2.

Specifically, if formula_6 is a Riemannian manifold (with or without boundary) and formula_7 is an immersed submanifold or an embedded submanifold (with or without boundary), the pullback formula_8 of formula_9 is a Riemannian metric on formula_1, and formula_11 is said to be a Riemannian submanifold of formula_6. On the other hand, if formula_1 already has a Riemannian metric formula_14, then the immersion (or embedding) formula_7 is called an [[isometric immersion]] (or [[isometric embedding]]) if formula_16. Hence isometric immersions and isometric embeddings are Riemannian submanifolds.

For example, the n-sphere formula_17 is an embedded Riemannian submanifold of formula_18 via the inclusion map formula_19 that takes a point in formula_20 to the corresponding point in the superset formula_18. The induced metric on formula_20 is called the round metric.

